---
title: Breakfast Bacon Quesadilla Stacks with Poblano Hash Browns, Avocado, and Bacon
description: The breakfast quesadilla is pretty under-the-radar in the scope of breakfast foods, outshone by its more popular cousins the breakfast taco and breakfast burrito. But considering that quesadillas are really just a grilled cheese disguised in a tortilla, they might be the most breakfast-worthy of all. This one is packed with spicy and savory elements, from a potato poblano hash to slices of crispy, mouthwatering bacon.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/w18-breakfast-dc4342a0.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/w18-breakfast-ec765687.pdf
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/breakfast-bacon-quesadilla-stacks-58cc2d9b3bddb5087f680b82
cuisine: North America
author: HelloFresh
course: main course
time required: 50 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 750 kcal
  fat: 42 g
  saturated fat: 13 g
  carbohydrates: 79 g
  sugar: 6 g
  protein: 19 g
  fiber: 12 g
  sodium: 730 mg
---

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high. Place half the @bacon{3%ounce} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Cook to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Halve and seed @poblano pepper{1}. Halve, peel, and mince @red onion{1}. Peel @russet potato{12%ounce}, then grate on large holes of a #box grater{}. Mince @jalapeño{1}, removing seeds for less heat.

Place poblano on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Broil until charred, about ~{5%minutes}. Let cool, then cut into ½-inch squares. Adjust oven temperature to 425 degrees. Meanwhile, place potato in another large pan with a pinch of @salt{pinch}, @vegetable oil{3%tsp}, and just enough water to cover. Bring to a boil and cook until water evaporates, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once water has evaporated, add another large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} to pan with potatoes and toss. Set aside 3 TBSP onion for salsa, then stir remainder into pan, along with poblano, half the jalapeño (use less to taste), and @Mexican spice blend{2%tsp} (we sent more). Cook, tossing, until onions are soft, ~{3-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Place four @flour tortilla{4} on same baking sheet. Toast in oven until slightly crispy, ~{5-6%minutes}. Meanwhile, finely chop @roma tomato{1}. Cut @lime{1} into wedges. Halve, pit, and scoop flesh from @avocado{1}, then thinly slice.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, reserved 3 TBSP onion, a big squeeze of lime juice, and as much of the remaining jalapeño as you like. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Divide hash between two tortillas on baking sheet. Sprinkle each with @Monterey jack cheese{1/2%cup}, then top with remaining tortillas. Bake in oven until cheese melts, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once quesadillas are done, divide between plates. Top each with bacon and avocado slices. Serve with salsa and lime wedges on the side for squeezing over.

> The breakfast quesadilla is under-the-radar in the scope of breakfast foods, but considering that quesadillas are really just a grilled cheese disguised in a tortilla, they might be the most breakfast-worthy of all. This one is packed with spicy and savory elements, from a potato poblano hash to slices of crispy, mouthwatering bacon.